We recommended that Management instruct     the Municipal Accounting Office to:

gather the details/information records, and other alternative documents needed to determine the components of local roads identified in the inventory; 

segregate and recognize the cost of each component of the local roads with identified cost and recognize component without corresponding cost at its fair value; 

depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and shall serve as the basis for recording in the general ledger; 

determine the life of the local roads within the range prescribed by COA taking into consideration the following factors:  a. design b. users c. volume of users; 

compute separately the depreciation for the road components taking into consideration the initial cost and useful life.

ensure that the details and information must be indicated in the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card - Local Road Network Ledger Card prepared and maintained for each item of road network;

re-compute the  accumulated depreciation and depreciation expense from CY 2016 to CY 2019 and thereafter adjust the affected accounts and the net book value of each of the asset;  and 

prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the year-end balance of the Public Infrastructure and Government Equity accounts.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Accounting Office to record receipt of fund transfers upon ensuring that source documents, particularly, the Memorandum of Agreement is attached to the Journal Voucher as required under COA Circular 2012-001;

direct the Municipal Accounting Office to ensure that entries in the subsidiary ledgers are consistently maintained and shall be kept necessary details to meet their needs and at the same time be adequate to furnish the information needed by fiscal or control agencies of the government.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to:
prepare bank reconciliation statements in a timely manner, compliant to COA Circular No. 96-011, for all funds of the Municipality as well as coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer in conducting such reconciliations;
investigate and validate the confirmed balance of the LGU’s General Fund with the management of LBP;
maintain subsidiary ledgers per bank account under Trust Fund to facilitate the monitoring and reconciling of the accounts with the depository banks; and
review entries made in the journals and subsidiary ledgers in order to fairly present the transactions of the Municipality.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
direct the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the projects with undetermined status and take proper actions on non-moving projects in coordination with other concerned department heads in-charge in order to return the unutilized funds to the NGAs concerned or otherwise request for authority to use said funds, if deemed appropriate;
require the Municipal Accountant to maintain accurate, appropriate and updated Subsidiary Ledgers on Due to NGAs account for proper monitoring.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

require the Municipal Accountant to identify the causes of the variance between differences of the unreconciled reciprocal accounts, trace and retrieve relevant documents to serve as basis in analyzing prior and current year reconciling items and prepare/effect the necessary adjustment, if any; 

reconcile the variance of ₱3.17 million between the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds consolidated balance at year end. These reciprocal accounts should have a zero consolidated balance at year end;

strictly adhere to COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 or the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units and pertinent provisions of P.D. 1445 on the proper account identification,  classification and recording particularly on the Due from/to Special Accounts for the General Fund Proper(01) and General Fund-LDF; and

establish the manner and frequency of reconciliation of reciprocal accounts. If possible, assign a focal person to do the reconciliation to be able to prioritize tracing, locating and retrieving relevant documents to serve as a basis for adjustment in the entries.

We recommended that Management:

prepare a complete LDRRMFIP that includes under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years;

refrain from charging disbursements against the LDRRMF which are not disaster-related and are disallowable under the governing provisions on its utilization;

refrain from transferring/realigning appropriations from one expense class to another in observance of Section 336 of RA 7160;

direct the Municipal DRRM Office to prepare and submit on a monthly basis the Report on Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF; and

instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain SLs in the Trust Fund books for every year of transfer of unexpended LDRRMF to ensure proper monitoring of the funds and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the prescribed disclosure of the details of LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management:

require the Accountable Officers concerned to settle/liquidate immediately their long outstanding cash advances and the concerned officials to adhere strictly to the rules and regulations in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances provided under COA Circular 97-002;

require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters and institute appropriate measures to enforce full liquidation of cash advances;  

ensure that outstanding cash advances are liquidated prior to separation from office by any appointed or elected officer or employee;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor initiate the following measures to ensure correctness of the Road Networks account: 

create an Inventory Committee, preferably composed one personnel each from the municipal Planning and Development Office; Engineering Office; Treasurer’s Office; General Services Office; Accountant’s Office and Assessor Office who shall conduct, on a full-time basis and within specified time, inspection and inventory of all road networks;

require the created inventory committee to conduct a physical count/inventory of all the municipal roads and reconcile it with the Municipal Road Map, if any and determine the existence and condition of the road components of each road for proper measurement and valuation using the prescribed forms such as: a)  Local Road and Bridge Inventory and Condition Survey; b)  Report of Local Road Network; and c) Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;

direct the Municipal Accounting Office to: gather all details and information needed to determine the cost of the road lot, road components and  depreciable life of each road network and reconcile it with the recorded cost in the Registry of Public Infrastructure and existing ledgers;  prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the recognition of Public Infrastructure - Roads, Highways and Bridges in the General Ledger amounting to ₱27,895,936.71 as of December 31, 2019 ensuring that the accounting and reporting procedures laid down under COA Circular 2015-008  are fully complied by the concerned offices while the same procedure shall be undertaken for other public infrastructures accounts; 

instruct the Municipal Accounting Office and the General Services Office to strictly prepare and maintain all the prescribed reports under COA Circular 2015-008; 

require the Municipal Planning and Development Office to maintain the information on the local road network of the MGG, particularly, the plans and programs of the construction, repair and maintenance of local roads and the depreciable life of the road networks in coordination with the Engineering Office;

direct the Municipal Engineering Office to ensure that the Local Road Network map is aligned to the requirement of a road map described under the DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2017-159 and Local Roads Assets Management Manual for LGUs;  and, as the Office that undertakes the construction and repair of the local roads, documents relative thereto shall be maintained so that the necessary and detailed information of a certain road project, such as complete description of the road and the cost segregation of the road components are available anytime needed by the accounting and general services office and other stakeholders;

require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to prepare and maintain the tax maps, which is used as basis for identifying the ownership of all the road lots in the of  city road network and shall  also assist in determining the cost of the road lots with no available costs; and 

instruct the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to gather and keep in her vault documents regarding the ownership or acquisition of road land or road right of way through purchase, donation or any other modes of acquisition.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit a duly certified list of the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year in accordance with Section 20 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs to serve as basis for the prospective recording of RPT and SET Receivables; 

enjoin the Municipal Accountant to record the SET Receivables and Deferred SET Income for CY 2019 amounting to ₱442,781.24 fairly present the financial statements.

We recommended that the Management:

exert best effort to acquire sanitary landfill or final disposal facility to facilitate observance of sound environmental practice like garbage collection and proper waste segregation; 

review its existing ten-year plan whether the following are included therein (i) concrete programs and projects that are supportive of proper solid waste managements and reduction of waste at source e.g. reuse, reduce and recycle of non- biodegradable materials ( ii) extent of the collection of garbage at the barangay level (iii) information and education campaigns on the hazards of open burning and strictly monitor compliance thereof specially at the barangay level ; and (iv) strengthening  its information campaign through  signage’s in public places displaying the acts prohibited under Section 48 of RA 9003 and the corresponding sanctions thereof.  Thereafter, follow-up the approval of the Solid Waste Management Plan from the National Solid Waste;

direct the concerned personnel for the effective usage of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) and strictly observe the provisions of RA 9003;  and 

coordinate with the Sangguniang Bayan, after consultation with the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board, to legislate ordinances to carry out the requirements of RA 9003 so that efficient management of solid waste will be effectively enforced and implemented.

We recommended that Management:

require the Accountable Officers concerned to settle/liquidate immediately their long outstanding cash advances and the concerned officials to adhere strictly to the rules and regulations in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances provided under COA Circular 97-002;

require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters and institute appropriate measures to enforce full liquidation of cash advances;  

ensure that outstanding cash advances are liquidated prior to separation from office by any appointed or elected officer or employee;

We recommended that Management: 

review the existing practices on inventory management and implement the Perpetual Inventory Method System in accounting for the receipts and issuances of supplies and materials required under the NGAS Manual for LGUs;

direct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain the pertinent Stock Cards for inventory items within and without their custody on the basis of AIRs for proper monitoring of the movement of inventory items;

enforce to the heads of offices/departments the immediate submission of relevant supporting documents upon distribution or consumption of the inventories under their custody for the timely preparation of SSMI by the Municipal Treasurer;

instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct periodic physical count of supplies and materials by type and prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), subject to reconciliation between records of the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer; and

enjoin the Municipal Accountant to stop from crediting Inventories account without the documentary requirements supporting actual consumption or distribution of inventories.

